  "target_response": {
    "text": "HRV — heart rate variability — is the variation in time between your heartbeats, measured overnight; a higher reading against your own norm generally signals a well-recovered nervous system, and your own trend is the only comparison that matters. Yours is steady. Today's reading is 64 ms, essentially at your 7-day average of 64.8 ms. That 64 ms is also a touch under your 30-day baseline of 64.9 ms — differences this small are day-to-day noise, not a trend. For a second anchor, your resting heart rate of 57 bpm is right on its 30-day baseline of 57.3 ms, which backs the same read: nothing to worry about. Keep judging HRV against your own 7-day and 30-day numbers rather than a universal target.",
